---
title: Crispy Sesame Rice & Sweet Heat Shrimp with Roasted Seaweed, Jalapeño, Creamy Chili Guac & Spicy Mayo
description: These crispy rice squares topped with sweet-spicy shrimp look like they came out of a restaurant! You’ll start by shaping and frying squares of seaweed-infused rice til they're crisp and golden brown. Top the rice with "sweet heat" shrimp tossed in spicy mayo and guacamole, then garnish with sesame seeds and scallions and dig right in.
image: https://img.hellofresh.com/f_auto,fl_lossy,h_640,q_auto,w_1200/hellofresh_s3/image/67c567c8c7d7f8f46885cd1e-f8fdbc16.jpeg
pdf: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipecards/card/67c567c8c7d7f8f46885cd1e-en-US.pdf
time required: 1 hour
course: main course
servings: 2
author: HelloFresh
cuisine: Southeast Asia
nutrition:
  calories: 1000 kcal
  fat: 48 g
  saturated fat: 8 g
  carbohydrates: 103 g
  sugar: 16 g
  protein: 29 g
  fiber: 4 g
  sodium: 1850 mg
source: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipes/crispy-sesame-rice-and-sweet-heat-shrimp-67c567c8c7d7f8f46885cd1e
---

Wash and dry produce. Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}, separating whites from greens. Thinly slice @jalapeño{1} into rounds, removing ribs and seeds for less heat.

Heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{} in a #small pot{} over medium-high heat. Add scallion whites; cook, stirring, until fragrant, ~{30%seconds}. Stir in @jasmine rice{1%cup}, half the @sesame seeds{2%tbsp}, @water{1 1/2%cups}, and a pinch of @salt{}; bring to a boil. Once boiling, cover and reduce to a low simmer. Cook until tender, ~{15-18%minutes}.

Keep covered off heat until ready to use in Step 3.

While rice cooks, in a #small bowl{}, whisk together @guacamole{4%tbsp}, half the @mayonnaise{2%tbsp}, and half the @Sriracha{1%tsp}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{} to taste. Reserve 1 TBSP creamy chili guac (2 TBSP for 4 servings) in a #medium bowl{} (set remaining creamy chili guac aside for serving).

Add @sweet Thai chili sauce{1%oz} to bowl with reserved creamy chili guac. Whisk to combine; set aside.

In a separate small bowl, whisk together remaining @mayonnaise{2%tbsp} and remaining @Sriracha{1%tsp}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{} to taste. Set aside.

Once rice is done, crumble half the @roasted seaweed sheets{1} into #pot{}. (Reserve remaining seaweed sheets for another use!) Using a #wooden spoon{}, stir until rice begins to stick together, ~{1%minute}. Add @rice wine vinegar{5%tsp}, @cornstarch{1%tbsp}, and @sugar{1%tsp}; stir until well combined.

Line an #8-by-8-inch baking dish{} with @plastic wrap{}. (TIP: Leave a little plastic wrap hanging over the sides of the dish so the rice is easier to remove in Step 5.) Coat with @nonstick cooking spray{}.

Using the back of a #spoon{}, press rice mixture into prepared #baking dish{} in an even layer. (TIP: Lightly coat surface of rice with nonstick cooking spray to help prevent it from sticking to the spoon.) Transfer to freezer until completely cooled, at least ~{15%minutes}.

Rinse @shrimp{10%oz} under cold water, then pat dry with #paper towels{}.

Heat a large drizzle of @cooking oil{} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add shrimp and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Cook, stirring occasionally, until shrimp are opaque and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}.

Transfer shrimp to medium bowl with sweet Thai chili guac. Stir to coat. Cover to keep warm.

Using plastic wrap overhang, carefully lift rice mixture out of baking dish and transfer to a #cutting board{} (discard plastic wrap). Cut into four equal squares (eight squares for 4 servings).

Heat a large drizzle of @cooking oil{} in a second large, preferably #nonstick pan{}, over medium-high heat. Add rice squares; cook until browned and crispy, ~{3-4%minutes} per side (you may need to cook in batches).

Transfer crispy rice squares to a #paper-towel-lined plate{}.

Divide crispy rice squares between plates. Spread each with remaining creamy chili guac, then top evenly with jalapeño and sweet heat shrimp. TIP: If desired, use less jalapeño to tame the heat.

Garnish with scallion greens and remaining @sesame seeds{2%tbsp}. Serve with spicy mayo on the side for dipping.

> Shellfish is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.